<P N="191">191. Vices may be &s;aid to wait for us in the cour&s;e of our lives, like the ho&s;ts of &s;o many inns, with whom &s;ucce&s;&s;ively we are forced to lodge; and I doubt whether experience would teach us to avoid them, if it was permitted us twice to travel the &s;ame road</P>
<P N="192">192. When vices leave us, we flatter our&s;elves with the belief that we leave them.</P>
<P N="193">193. There are relap&s;es in the di&s;tempers of the &s;oul, as in tho&s;e of the body; what we take for a cure, is mo&s;t commonly nothing but an abatement, or a change of di&s;ea&s;e.</P>
