<P N="211">211. There are &s;ome men, like ballads, in reque&s;t only for a while.</P>
<P N="212">212. The generality of the wo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ld never judge of men, but by their reputation or by their fortune.</P>
<P N="213">213. The love of glory, the fear of &s;hame, the de&s;ign of making a fortune, the de&s;ire of rendering life ea&s;y and agreeable, and a malici|ous humour of pulling down others, are often the cau&s;es of that va|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">our &s;o much celebrated among men.</P>
<P N="214">214. Valour in private &s;oldiers is a hazardous trade they have tak|en up to get a livelihood by.</P>
<P N="215">215. Perfect courage and co<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">plete cowardice are two extremes which men &s;eldom arrive to. The &s;pace that is between them is va&s;t, and contains all the other &s;orts of courage: which differs too no le&s;s
